<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900510-0085</DOCNO><DOCID>900510-0085.</DOCID><HL>   Aerospace, Aerospatiale Study</HL><DATE>05/10/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   U.BA F.ASP</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><LP>   PARIS -- British Aerospace PLC and Aerospatiale of Franceconfirmed they will conduct a five-year study to decidewhether to develop a new supersonic airliner to replace theirjointly produced Concorde.   The final decision on whether to proceed with a $10billion dollar production program will be made in 1995,Aerospatiale President Henri Martre said.</LP><TEXT>   He said the feasibility study, which would cost about $34million dollars, would focus on such issues as marketpotential, technical factors and environmental protection.   Mr. Martre said the British and French companies wouldwelcome cooperation with other industrial powers, includingthe U.S., Soviet Union, West Germany and Japan.   British Airways and Air France together operate 13Concordes on trans-Atlantic routes. These planes are due forretirement within 15 to 20 years; the new planes, ifdeveloped, would be ready by about 2005.   The projected aircraft would be capable of nonstop flightsacross the Pacific.</TEXT></DOC>